## Documentation structure template

Follow this structure when creating new documentation pages. Adjust as needed based on content type.

### Standard structure

#### 1. Frontmatter

```yaml
---
title: Clear, descriptive title
# Optional: left navigation label (Title Case). Omit when it should match `title`.
sidebar_label: Title Case Label For Sidebar
description: One-sentence summary of what this guide covers
keywords:
  - keyword1
  - keyword2
  - keyword3
tags:
  - tag1
  - tag2
  - tag3
---
```

- **`title`:** Official page title (browser, SEO, and default sidebar label). May use phrasing that fits the page better than the nav.
- **`sidebar_label`:** Use when the **sidebar** label must differ from `title`. Sidebar labels use **Title Case** (capitalize major words). If omitted, Docusaurus derives the sidebar entry from `title`.

#### 2. Introduction (2-3 lines)

- **Paragraph 1**: What is this feature/capability?
- **Paragraph 2**: Why use it? What problems does it solve?
- **Paragraph 3**: Key benefits or use cases

##### What will you learn?

Optionally include a brief list of key outcomes or topics covered in this guide:

```markdown
## What will you learn?

- **Topic 1:** Brief description of what they'll learn.
- **Topic 2:** Another key outcome or skill.
- **Topic 3:** Additional learning objective.
```

#### 3. Prerequisites

List required setup, permissions, or knowledge. **For each prerequisite**, tell the reader how to satisfy it; don't assume they already have it.

- **"Module or feature enabled" (e.g. IaCM enabled):** State **where it appears in the UI** when available (e.g. **Infrastructure** > **Infrastructure as Code Management**). For **account access** (sign-up, SaaS vs self-managed, invitations), link to [Getting started with Harness Platform](/docs/platform/get-started/onboarding-guide)—do **not** ask readers to identify their deployment model up front. Put **if the module does not appear** guidance in a `:::info Contact Harness support:` admonition **indented with four spaces** under that prerequisite bullet so it nests in the list; inside the admonition, link the module get-started page (e.g. [Get started with IaCM](/docs/infra-as-code-management/get-started)), then account administrator or [Harness Support](mailto:support@harness.io). Add **self-hosted enablement** or **what’s supported** links only when the doc’s audience is clearly administrators or advanced users, not first-time onboarding.
- **Permissions (e.g. "permission to create and run pipelines"):** Name the **specific permissions** (e.g. View, Create/Edit, Execute for Pipelines), link to the [Permissions reference](/docs/platform/role-based-access-control/permissions-reference) (use the relevant anchor, e.g. `#pipelines`), and say **how to get them** (e.g. an administrator must assign a role that includes them) with a link to [RBAC in Harness](/docs/platform/role-based-access-control/rbac-in-harness) and/or [Manage roles](/docs/platform/role-based-access-control/add-manage-roles).
- **Other items:** Link to how/where if a new user might not have it.

```markdown
## Prerequisites

- **Harness account with IaCM enabled:** You need **Infrastructure as Code Management** under **Infrastructure** in Harness when it is entitled on your account. For how to access or create a Harness account, see [Getting started with Harness Platform](/docs/platform/get-started/onboarding-guide).

    :::info Contact Harness support:

    If IaCM does not appear, see [Get started with IaCM](/docs/infra-as-code-management/get-started) or contact your account administrator or [Harness Support](mailto:support@harness.io).

    :::

- **Pipeline permissions:** You need **View**, **Create/Edit**, and **Execute** for [Pipelines](/docs/platform/role-based-access-control/permissions-reference#pipelines). To get these, an administrator must assign you a role that includes them. See [RBAC in Harness](/docs/platform/role-based-access-control/rbac-in-harness) and [Manage roles](/docs/platform/role-based-access-control/add-manage-roles).
- **Item 3**
```

For modules other than IaCM, keep the same pattern: **UI location** when entitled, [Getting started with Harness Platform](/docs/platform/get-started/onboarding-guide) for account access, then a `:::info Contact Harness support:` admonition (indented under that bullet with four spaces so it nests in the prerequisite list) with module **get started** plus administrator or [Harness Support](mailto:support@harness.io) if the module does not appear.

#### 4. Step-by-step instructions

Use clear, numbered sections with **imperative** headers in **sentence case** (e.g. `## Create an inventory`, not gerunds like "Creating an inventory"). Capitalize **proper nouns**: product and technology names (e.g. **Kubernetes**, **Terraform**, **OpenTofu**, **Harness**, **IaCM**, **AWS**) and official **Harness** UI feature names when they are branded or module names.

- **Get started guides — `## Step 1`, `## Step 2`, etc.:** For **onboarding / get started** pages only, you may use numbered step headings (e.g. `## Step 1: Add connectors`) to emphasize a short, linear path. This is an **exception** to the usual imperative-phrase section titles. Use it **only for actionable procedure**—the body of the guide where the user does things in order. Do **not** use `## Step N` for **Prerequisites**, **Troubleshooting**, or **Next steps** (keep those sections titled as noun phrases or fixed labels like `## Prerequisites`, `## Troubleshooting`, `## Next steps`). Do not label introductory or conceptual blocks as steps.
- **Step groups:** When several steps form a logical group (e.g. module details), add a **heading for that group** (e.g. `### Module details`) and nest the steps under it (e.g. `#### Step 1`, `#### Step 2`). Add a **one-line summary** under the group heading so the reader knows what those steps accomplish (e.g. "The following steps (1–3) configure the module name, provider, connector, and storage type.").
- **Intro before lists:** **Always add a short intro sentence before every numbered or bullet list** that states what the list is for or what the reader is about to do. Do not jump straight into "1. Select...". This helps readers and LLMs understand context (e.g. "On the Execution pipeline step of the wizard, do the following:" then "1. Select a pipeline...").
- **UI elements:** **Bold all clickable or selectable UI elements** in steps: menu names, buttons, tabs, checkboxes, dropdowns, field labels. Use the same convention everywhere; do not mix bold and plain for the same type of element (e.g. every button like **Create**, **Sync**, **Next** should be bold).
- **Unfamiliar actions:** When the doc tells the user to do something they might not know how to do (e.g. "run manual sync", "create the pipeline manually"):
  - If it's explained **elsewhere in the same doc**, link to that section (e.g. "For how to run the manual sync, see [Step 6: Create and run the initial sync](#step-6-create-and-run-the-initial-sync).").
  - If it's **"create X manually"**, give the UI path (e.g. "Go to **Infrastructure** > **Pipelines** > **Create a Pipeline** in your project") and link to the doc that describes it (e.g. "see [Harness Pipelines](/docs/category/pipelines)").

```markdown
## Step 1: Create an inventory

Instructions here.

:::tip
Add troubleshooting hints inline when they help anticipate common issues.
:::

## Step 2: Register a playbook

More instructions.
```

**When to include inline troubleshooting:**

- Common errors that happen during this specific step
- Configuration gotchas that prevent progress
- Quick fixes that keep the user moving forward

#### 5. Troubleshooting section (optional)

Only include if there are general issues not tied to specific steps.

Use the `<Troubleshoot>` component from `AdaptiveAIContent` — do **not** use static `### heading` + `**Solution:**` pairs. The component renders a collapsible entry sourced from live docs (Kapa) or pre-generated AI responses (Gemini), with a static fallback.

Import at the top of the file (after frontmatter):

```mdx
import { Troubleshoot } from '@site/src/components/AdaptiveAIContent';
```

Then in the body:

```markdown
## Troubleshooting
```

```jsx
<Troubleshoot
  issue="[Concise description of the problem, including product/module context for Kapa]"
  mode="docs"
  fallback="[One-sentence static fix shown if AI is unavailable]"
/>
```

**Choosing `mode`:**

- `mode="docs"` — Harness-specific issues (error codes, pipeline behaviour, module config). Kapa answers at runtime from live docs. Use for most entries.
- `mode="general"` — Infrastructure-adjacent issues (auth, networking, Terraform, Kubernetes). Gemini pre-generates a response at build time.
- `mode="fallback-only"` — Deterministic fixes where the answer never changes. Always shows the `fallback`; no AI call is made.

**Rules:**

- Do **not** add `###` headings above each component — the `issue` prop serves as the collapsible heading.
- The `fallback` prop is required on every entry.
- Write `issue` with enough context for Kapa to match the right docs (include product name, module, or error message text).
- Multiple entries sit directly adjacent with no headings between them.

**Example:**

```jsx
<Troubleshoot
  issue="Error acquiring the state lock in Harness IaCM pipeline with remote backend"
  mode="docs"
  fallback="Ensure no other process is holding a lock. Lock retries are handled automatically by OpenTofu/Terraform."
/>

<Troubleshoot
  issue="Concurrent operations conflict on the same Terraform state file with remote backend"
  mode="general"
  fallback="Each backend handles locking independently — DynamoDB for S3, object metadata for GCS, leases for Azure Blob."
/>
```

#### 6. Next steps

Wrap up with:

- **Brief conclusion** (1-2 sentences): Summarize what was accomplished
- **2-3 related links**: Most logical next actions or related docs

```markdown
## Next steps

You've successfully [accomplished X]. You can now [key capability unlocked].

- [Related doc 1]
- [Related doc 2]
- [Related doc 3]
```

### Markdown headings and sidebar

- **No `#` (h1) in the file body.** Do not use a single-hash heading in Markdown. Start the document body at `##`. The page still has an official title via frontmatter `title` (and Docusaurus may render it per theme).
- **Sentence case for in-doc headings (`##`, `###`, …):** Capitalize the **first word** only, except for **proper nouns**: technologies (e.g. **Docker**, **Kubernetes**, **GitHub**), **Harness** modules and products (e.g. **IaCM**, **STO**, **CD** when referring to the module), and other trademarked or official names. Examples: `## Create a pipeline`, `## Configure the IaCM plugin`, `## Install a Kubernetes delegate`.
- **Sidebar labels (navigation):** Use **Title Case** — capitalize major words in the left nav. Set this with **`sidebar_label`** when it needs to read differently from `title`, or shape the **`title`** itself in Title Case if it doubles as the sidebar label and matches the nav wording you want.

### Content guidelines

- **Headers:** Imperative, sentence case; no gerunds in step titles (prefer `## Configure the connector` over `## Configuring the connector`). Exception: concept sections may use noun phrases (`## Troubleshooting`, `## Prerequisites`). **Get started** guides may use `## Step 1`, `## Step 2`, … **only** for actionable onboarding steps—not for Prerequisites, Troubleshooting, or Next steps. Gerunds are fine for broad concepts like "Understanding CI/CD" when that fits the content.
- **Lists:** When each item has a concept/action and an explanation, use **Bold label:** description. For simple self-explanatory lists, plain formatting is fine. Always add a short intro sentence before a list that states what the list is for.
- Keep prerequisites minimal and relevant; link to "how" for each.
- Include code examples where helpful.
- Use callouts (`:::tip`, `:::warning`, `:::info`) strategically.
- Link to related concepts inline, not just at the end.
